posts.sub: Let's discuss the grueling recording sessions that produced Danger Days.
posts.com:
For those that aren't aware, My Chemical Romance's fourth album finally came together after a lengthy gestation and multiple aborted attempts.

During promo for Danger Days, the narrative was that the band had been poised to release a raw, back to basics record, but they weren't truly enthusiastic about it. The band recorded Na Na Na in a burst of inspiration and were so excited about it they put the hold on the planned record. They spent the next few months quickly writing songs that weren't so limited in concept - embracing pop hooks, synths, etc. So the story goes, this produced Danger Days.

Some of those previous aborted sessions were released in 2013 as a series of singles titled Conventional Weapons.

There's a misconception among many fans that Conventional Weapons IS the previous record. It's not.

I remember following the recording their fourth album in 2009-2010. The reality is a bit more complicated than the narrative. They actually trashed not just one record, but two before finally releasing Danger Days.

The first of these was the true "back to basics" concept. The goal was to create the anti-Black Parade - to strip away ornate arrangements and anthemic choruses, to sound like the MC5 and Iggy Pop. They were basically trying to run away from their "emo" image.

These sessions, completed by summer of 2009, reportedly resulted in between 10-13 songs, including:

Death Before Disco (later released on Danger Days as "Party Poison")

LA Heavy (known also as "Hail the King" and ultimately released on CW as "Kiss the Ring")

Drugs (never released)

Upon test-driving these songs live alongside their previous work, the band lost faith that the material was strong enough and decided to "start again."

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
Some songs survived, but the back-to-basics concept was more or less dropped here. The band went back to work, this time with the intent to embrace their strengths rather than run from them. Anthemic choruses and melodic hooks were reintroduced into the songwriting. Interviews around this time suggested a vague concept of the album being a "love letter to rock'n'roll" - but this time the influences were not just proto-punk, but as varied as Judas Priest, Pink Floyd, and Bruce Springsteen.

With these additional sessions, a total of 21 songs were reportedly completed. By the fall of 2009, this total batch included

Trans Am (released on DD as "Bulletproof Heart")
The Only Hope for Me is You (released on DD)
The Light Behind Your Eyes (released on CW)
Still Alive (unreleased)
Save Yourself, I'll Hold Them Back (released on DD)
Black Dragon Fighting Society (released on the Mad Gear and Missile Kid EP)

The second proposed album, slated to be released in spring of 2010, would have contained some combination of songs from both the previous and second sessions. It was rumored to be titled "Save Yourself, I'll Hold Them Back," which was also to be the lead single.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
It was this second album that was aborted after the writing of Na Na Na. With this third burst of inspiration, the band finally overcame their self-imposed restrictions and put together a set of songs that they felt stood alongside their previous work in ambition and boundary-pushing.

Still, obviously many songs survived. The only songs we can be reasonably sure were written during the summer of 2010 are the following:

Na Na Na
SING
Planetary (Go!)
S/C/A/R/E/C/R/O/W
Summertime
Destroya
The Kids from Yesterday

The sequence of songs on Conventional Weapons, then, was clearly never intended to be released as an album. Any planned release would have included the songs that survived to Danger Days.

By my count, this means that at least 28 songs were recorded over 2009-2010. Of these 28,

>12 were released on Danger Days
>2 were released as b-sides (Zero Percent and We Don't Need Another Song About California)
>3 were released on the Mad Gear and Missile Kid EP
>10 were released on Conventional Weapons

This is assuming that all 5 of the EP tracks and b-sides were in the 21 completed the previous fall. Even with this conservative estimate, that means 3 songs remain unreleased - we know two of these are Still Alive and Drugs.

A few questions -

Can you identify by name any other songs from this period that aren't accounted for, or that I've left off?

What tracks do you think came from which sessions (first, second, or third)?

What would the track listing for the cancelled album/s have been?

Will more from this period ever come to light?

>>114456736
Good blasting so let me spoonfeed you.

Altec Lansing makes decent desktop speakers, look for one with a sub. They're affordable and good quality.
Let me explain. I have Altec Lansings VS 4121 that came out in 2004. A friend gave them to me but according to the Internet they cost less than a hundred bucks. The model consists of two speakers and a sub. The speakers are pretty precise, but the sub makes all the difference. You can turn the trebles and bass up and down directly on the speaker, with the middle being 0. Now, with the trebles you don't hear a huge difference, yet it's nice to be able to tweak them ; with the bass, when you go below a certain threshold (about 2/3 below zero) the sub starts speaking Black Speech, it's like sitting in the void of space. Yet if you keep it in these 2/3 below zero, you still have enough bass to make the floor tremble. Putting the bass at 0 will make two stars appear in your top left field of view. So I keep my trebles at 1/2 over 0 and the bass at 1/2 below zero, and the sound is perfect.
So yeah, try to look for Altec Lansings with a sub. They're pretty cool. Not the best quality but great for the price.

Scream Aim Fire was the very metal album I ever bought, back when I was like 9 or 10 years old. It's been a downward spiral ever since. Good album. I also have the B4MV album that came after, with the topless chick on the cover. Not as good.

>>114446474
The middle pickup is mostly pointless for a beginner. Sure, technically, it's one more pickup and has its own tone, but it's diminishing returns unless you're Bootsy Collins.

Tremolo bridges require routing & reshaping of wood in the middle of the body, so you can't really add one in the practicable sense. Such a job would be many hundreds of dollars just for labor. Look up tremolo bridges to get an idea of cost of parts. It would also require advanced skills & tooling and I'll bet most guitar luthiers of that skillset would refuse a job like that, perhaps even laugh at you.

>>114455049
>I downloaded music theory for dummies. Will reading that make me understand what you're saying?
Maybe. Just google "natural minor scale guitar" and write down the tab. That's what you should learn over A minor/C minor whatever. It's marginally more complex but 90% of rock and metal uses the natural/melodic/harmonic minors. Especially a lot of 70's classic rock.
What helped me wasn't to think in "key". My retard ADHD brain could only think in tabs when I was starting out. Take this chart. You don't have to know what the actual key is, you're not actually learning the whole fretboard. You're learning the starting point and playing the scale from there. Basically your starting position is what key you're in. When I understood that from a tab perspective, that was a major breakthrough for me. I didn't learn D on B string. I thought 3rd fret on 3rd position. Then I played the scale from there. I tried to end and begin my runs on chord shapes I learned from the songs I played to make it sound less like random notes. Like I said, when you get somewhat competent, then really dive into circle of fifths. It's easier to learn when it's something you've already been doing. Then when you actually understand key and scales, you won't play any more "bad notes" or just noodle around.

That's the whole point. The self-loathing, whining and unbelievably obnoxious sounds and themes are what makes Jihad attractive to some, they're a "hate it or love it" band, you either get it or don't because for those who don't, their presences already repels them from investigating further. Jumping into the deep end isn't an option because like most medium the unknown discourages, not to mention bringing your own personal biases and assumptions, rendering the whole ordeal obsolete.

Personally their music is a window to the lives and thoughts of the inaction liberal millennial, someone whose passion lies more on whining with music than improving society, someone who rather feel sorry for himself through pity than giving and receiving advice(s).

From a technical perspective, they're one of the standouts within the folk punk and anti-folk scene, this gives them a huge advantage on pushing their themes much forward to the listeners. If they were a bunch of retards who plays 2 chords for 3 minutes complaining about social welfare and equality, I wouldn't be wasting my time with this post. Not many can do what they do musically, even if their lyricism differs or changes, one would still return just for their technical skill in their respective genre.

Like most art, it's suppose to challenge your perspective, both sonically and through ideas. If it makes you uncomfortable, it may (and I'm making a huge assumption here) be because it's speaking about a certain guilt manifested within you, you don't want to admit it or face it so instinctively your mind copes by giving you the unpleasant natural response of fighting back, cringing, and that's what Jihad's greatest skill lies at.

Ultimately listening to them is like watching a good horror movie, but instead of getting a good scare, you get a good cringe. They're a master of what they do and one of my favorite musical act.

Vaporwave is a unique and innovative genre of electronic music that has pushed the boundaries of what music can be. Its use of slowed-down, chopped-up samples of 1980s and 1990s pop music creates a surreal, nostalgic atmosphere that is unlike anything else in the music world. Its commentary on consumer culture and the nostalgia of the digital age is both thought-provoking and relatable, and its incorporation of visual elements such as glitch art and retro computer graphics adds an extra layer of depth to the music. In addition, the genre has been influential in the development of other styles of electronic music, making it a crucial part of the musical landscape. Overall, vaporwave's unique sound and cultural significance make it a standout among other genres of music.

Vaporwave is a highly intellectual and sophisticated art form that is sure to be appreciated by all the most pretentious hipsters out there. It's a genre of music that is essentially just a bunch of poorly made beats and samples from old 80s and 90s tracks, but with some added echo effects for that extra touch of depth and complexity. It's all about being edgy and alternative and pretending to be super deep and artistic, even though it's really just a bunch of recycled nostalgia. But hey, if that's your thing, then more power to you, vaporwave aficionado. So, in short, vaporwave is a parody of itself.

>>114441662

(1/2)

Nothing in the wrist without the fingers, nothing in the fingers without the wrist. That's quote from some famous Soviet piano mentor but I forgot who.
If you're playing multiple notes in rapid succession, there's a tendency to offload all or almost all the motion and work to the wrist, with insufficient engagement of the fingers. This causes tension to accumulate and concentrate in the wrist, leading to the wrist locking up and then causing carpal tunnel syndrome in the long-term.
You want to create a smooth kinetic chain in your technique, with every keystroke involving a concerted and controlled synergistic motion of the finger, wrist, (and also forearm, shoulder, etc). But the finger/wrist synergy is by far the most important.
You may think you're using your fingers (duh you're playing the piano), but if your wrist tends to lock up when playing a particular passage or piece, then that's a dead giveaway that you're actually not. It's more than likely you're just moving the upper parts of the fingers (the parts of the fingers closest to the palm of the hand, in between the 1st and 2nd knuckles), which still rely largely on the tendons in the wrist.
What you want is a curling motion in the lower parts of your fingertips, the parts of the fingers after the 2nd knuckles. This motion has a slightly different locus of tension, more in the palm of the hand. If you combine these motions into one kinetic chain, your tension will be more smoothly distributed and you'll get more relaxation and mobility. At the very least it'll go from your wrist into your forearms. That's still not ideal, and you might still experience lock-ups but it's far less dangerous and painful. Beyond that it comes down to conscious mental relaxation and improving your kinetic chain, which is a longer-term task.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114441662

(2/2)

Here's something piano teachers will kill me for saying: sometimes you just need to practice speed for its own sake. (But you need to be smart about it obviously). You can't expect to gain speed and relaxation efficiently by always practicing slow and steady and gradually speeding up. The fact is that playing the same passage slow and fast sometimes involves very different patterns of motion, despite the sequence of notes being exactly the same. Sometimes the fingerings will be completely different. Playing the same passage presto leggiero and lento pesante will be a very different kinesthetic experience with different executional considerations. Practicing a passage at a slow tempo won't necessarily give you a foray into the experience of the kinds of movements you'll be using to play it fast. And by the way, it works the other way round too (it's called fast play degeneration).
So if you're looking to build speed, it helps to alternate between fast and slow. Play a passage twice focusing on pure speed without much consideration for wrong notes and "proper" technique, and then follow up with 2 playthroughs at very slow tempo with perfect accuracy and technique. Then play it slightly faster, and so on. Vary the tempo; slow and steady runs serve to "anchor" the gains from the fast ones.

Finally, don't be a stranger to arm/forearm stretches. No matter how hard you try to follow these principles, you won't be able to avoid tension altogether, and if you practice often for long periods, that tension will accumulate and at that point no amount of technique will help. At times you'll just need to relieve the tension manually, and that comes in the form of a couple wrist stretches.
Unironically aikido has some good ones, also look up "nerve flossing" exercises on physiotherapy channels. I have my own forearm stretch exercise set that I developed for my own use.

>>114441662

(3/2)

Oh I forgot to mention the most important thing. Strengthen and train the weaker part of the hand (fingers 3,4,5). Those are the ones which you will mostly fail to engage properly. Especially your pinky finger (finger 5). Play lots of Chopin, he's got all those melodic lines in the alto register played by fingers 4,5 that need to be brought out while the 1,2,3 play the quieter middle voices. It's good practice for finger independence and dynamic control. Or if you're masochistically inclined or just very motivated, print out a little something called Op. 10 No. 2 and start playing through that nice and slowly.
Don't neglect your left hand either.
I've noticed that the more virtuosic the piece, the better your pinky fingers need to be in order to play it properly. The correlation is pretty rock solid.

>>114449147
I hate to be that guy, but the first 2 chopin etudes are very simple structurally and can be practiced even by novices at slow tempo. The first one can be taken as is, since it's just octaves and the same arpeggio configurations repeated the whole way through.
As for the second one, you can remove the left hand entirely and practice just the right hand part. If you want, you can remove the middle voice too and practice only the melodic line in the very top notes.
I honestly can't think of anything better to grind for developing strength and dexterity (and getting used to reading/playing notes across the whole piano register rather than just the 2 middle octaves). Playing real, actual pieces is the best practice you can get, and they actually sound good, so you won't get as bored of hearing and playing them over and over again as you would with more generic "beginner" pieces.
Just make sure you take it slow and steady.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
Unironically the vinyl subreddit has a lot of really good and important information.

Nonetheless, it's important to remember the concept of bottlenecking when it comes to setups. Good rule of thumb that your speakers should cost roughly the same amount as your turntable. It's very, very easy to get carried away and believe the other dorks who tell you that you need every upgrade and expensive shit under the sun. That said, lower-end turntables use pretty sub-par carts, wonky tonearms and other misc things that results in more wear and tear on your records.

Since you're asking for higher-end, here's personally what I use
>Project Evo Carbon (~$600, you will never need more)
>pre-amp of choice in the ~$150 price-range. Rega Mini is good, project's is pretty good too (can't remember name), basically can just google reviews and pick whatever one strikes your fancy
>speakers are tough. i'd check your local craigslist or whatever and see what you can get used, as newer ones tend to be really expensive. again, spend roughly the same amount you'll spend on the turntable, but used changes things up.
>reciever is also tough to recommend, check local listings. might be able to snag one with a phono already inside of it which saves you buying a pre-amp if you wanna test the waters and not dump a bunch of cash all at once
>buy all your records used from discog (and new too, but VG+ records on there will sound literally new and you'll save a lot)
enjoy! vinyls are a really fun thing to collect and listen to, plus it's always a great conversation thing when friends come over.

Depends on what you are looking for really.
Party hard, dance clubs etc, then Stockholm, maybe Gothenburg.
If you want to be at the top of the world for nature and stuff then go to Kiruna (far north). Or be surrounded by trees, then any city north and west (towards Norway) of Stockholm.

If you want to experience daily life for any Swede then smaller cities, maybe Karlstad, Skellefteå, Östersund, Kalmar, Örebro, and the connecting villages to each city.

History stuff? Then Visby (Gotland), Gothenburg, Stockholm, Lund and Uppsala.

Exotic stuff, Malmö...

technique aside, learning how the scales relate to chords and how to make chord voicings is the very most important part of piano

everything else is basically just general music knowlegde (like how to write a song, having good taste, history, gear etc) BUT the harmonic quality of a piano is so essential to it's sound that you are better off learning how to relate scales under chords right now.

It's not as hard as it seems, learn how to make diads (learn the intervals) triads (major, minor and diminished/augmented chords) and how to relate the major and minor scale to the major/minor chords. So you can spreed the notes across the keys and use different scales/chords the same way

AND then how to add extensions and how to spreed those notes across the octaves.

With that, you are pretty much off to just learn technique and just general ideas about music rather than not

Occasionally sure you have your Justin Bieber or Beabadoobee, or Billie Eilish, who stumble into fame from having a cushy life mostly based on the fact they’re attractive, which if you have those kinda looks definitely utilize it. And even more rarely you have some attractive musicians who have it on easymode and still grind like Taylor Swift or David Bowie.

>How big is your local language?
Total population of about 25 million people, in the richer part of Europe (Flanders/Netherlands).
There's a still-popular tradition of music in the local language, both country-esque (Schlager) and modern pop music.
Bands like Bazart and Goldband sing in the local language, and they do very well, even headlining major festivals.

There are even foreign bands like Editors that survive almost entirely on their Flemish audience.
